<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-942-540  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 942 540.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Nov 8 1989 n119 p167(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New Hackers's Handbook.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Beattie, Rob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Hackers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>New Hacker's HandbookandM;Not such a curious choice for inclusion here as you might think, becausealongside some interesting anecdotes, there's a lot of hard technicalinformation for the communications novice, and some good stuff on esotericthings like radio communications for experienced users.andM;The book is contemporary enough to cover V.42 and LAP-M, and thoughtfulenough to include a glossary of technical terms, some useful troubleshootingtips, and excerpts from bulletin board conversations.andM;In his ground-breaking book Out Of The Inner Circle, Bill Landreth calls hishackers 'explorers' and points out that they are interested in the science ofthe 'hack' itself rather than any financial gain.andP;  The authors here concur,and liken hacking to an evening stroll through an interesting landscape --until 1985, which as Cornwall observes: &quot;...was the year in which hackers hadto think carefully about the ethics of hacking.andP;  Until then, hacking's elitequality seemed to provide sufficient control to prevent matters gettingout-of-hand.&quot;andP;  After that, of course, came the so-called Great Prestel Hack(Prince Philip's almost unused mailbox), and the arrest of Edward AustinSingh who was accused of going around Prime Computer networks via SurreyUniversity.andM;The main drawback with the book is that the authors don't really touch onwhat drives hackers.andP;  There's the 'explorer' analogy, and some passages abouthackers highlighting poor security procedures, but it's all a bitunconvincing.andP;  Thus you'll probably come out as you went in -- eitheradmiring their derring-do or wondering when their antics are going to stop.andO;There's some good technical stuff, though.andO;</TEXT></DOC>